{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474925"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:27:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:27:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12472"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12472"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.29,0.17,0.25,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4979"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46189"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4979"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12472"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31114"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4836"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8239"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8476"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8551"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34086"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43888"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46189"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old girl presents to her General Practice clinic with her parents with a three-month history of intermittent abdominal pain. She has been constipated, only passing one to two stools per week. Despite having been toilet trained six months ago, she has had three episodes of faecal incontinence over the past two weeks. She started childcare four months ago and the parents are unsure whether she is passing stool at childcare. She has not vomited and the parents are not concerned about weight loss or poor growth. She has no other significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with a pulse rate of 100/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Her abdomen is generally tender but the pain is distractible. There is a palpable mass in the left lower quadrant.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increase dietary fibre","Commence oral stool disimpaction regimen","Abdominal X-ray","Commence using a sticker chart to reinforce positive toileting behaviour","Commence macrogol or polyethylene glycol (PEG) 3350 daily"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with \u003Cstrong\u003Efunctional constipation\u003C/strong\u003E. Functional constipation is common, especially during times of transition in a child\u0027s life such as starting solid foods, toilet training and childcare or school commencement. Functional constipation is diagnosed using the Rome IV Criteria. A patient must have \u22652 criteria for at least one month in infants or two months in older children:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u22642 defecations per week\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHistory of excessive stool retention\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHistory of painful or hard bowel movements\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHistory of large-diameter stools\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPresence of a large fecal mass in the rectum\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn toilet-trained children, the following additional criteria may be used:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAt least one episode/week of incontinence after the acquisition of toileting skills\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHistory of large-diameter stools that may obstruct the toilet\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther causes of abdominal pain are unlikely due to the lack of red flag symptoms such as weight loss/poor growth and persistent vomiting. The abdominal mass may be concerning, however it is likely palpable feces considering the longstanding constipation and the location of the mass in the sigmoid colon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs this child is experiencing persistent abdominal pain, encopresis and has fecal loading on examination, \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral stool disimpaction\u003C/strong\u003E is required. High doses of macrogol are used for stool disimpaction and should be continued for several days until there is a large amount of stool passed, and then maintenance stool softeners are continued for at least three months. This can all be done as an outpatient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing dietary fibre\u003C/strong\u003E is not an adequate treatment for constipation and should not be first line advice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations are not required if the clinical diagnosis is functional constipation without any red flags. An \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary at this point.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBehavior modifications such as using a \u003Cstrong\u003Esticker chart to reinforce positive toileting behaviour\u003C/strong\u003E is helpful in the long-term management of functional constipation, however it is not the most helpful next step in management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMaintenance treatment with \u003Cstrong\u003Emacrogol or polyethylene glycol (PEG) 3350 daily\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate following disimpaction, and should be continued for at least three months.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Severe functional constipation should be managed with disimpaction.","Functional constipation is common during childhood transitions such as starting solid foods, toilet training, and childcare or school commencement."],"references":["The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Constipation [Internet]. Victoria, Australia. 2020 March [cited 2023 Feb]. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Constipation/","Tabbers MM, DiLorenzo C, Berger MY, et al. Evaluation and treatment of functional constipation in infants and children: evidence-based recommendations from ESPGHAN and NASPGHAN. J Pediatr Gastroenterol Nutr [Internet]. 2014 [cited 2023 Feb];58(2):258-274. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24345831/","Diaz S, Bittar K, Mendez MD. Constipation. StatPearls [Internet]. 2022 Jan [cited 2023 Feb]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK513291/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31114"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12472"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31114"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-30T19:44:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-20T17:51:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4979"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46189"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","lin